---
import Base from '~/layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Code of Conduct — PGConf Poland 2026"
  description="PGConf Poland 2026 follows the PostgreSQL Europe Code of Conduct. Read the full text and how to report concerns."
>
  <article class="coc">
    <header class="coc-head">
      <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="eyebrow">Conference policies</p>
        <h1 class="coc-title">Code of Conduct</h1>
        <p class="coc-lede">
          PGConf Poland 2026 follows the PostgreSQL Europe Code of Conduct.
          We are committed to providing a friendly, safe, and welcoming
          environment for everyone — regardless of background, identity, or
          experience level. This page summarises the policy in plain language
          and explains how to report a concern.
        </p>
        <div class="rule"></div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="coc-body">
      <div class="container container--prose">
        <section>
          <h2>Our commitment</h2>
          <p>
            PGConf Poland is dedicated to a harassment-free conference
            experience for everyone. The conference team, speakers, sponsors,
            and attendees are all expected to uphold this commitment for the
            duration of the event — in talks, workshops, hallway conversations,
            social events, and online channels associated with the conference.
          </p>
          <p>
            This applies regardless of gender, gender identity and expression,
            sexual orientation, disability, neurotype, physical appearance,
            body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, nationality, or
            technical experience. We do not tolerate harassment of conference
            participants in any form.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Unacceptable behaviour</h2>
          <p>The following are examples of behaviour we will not tolerate:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Offensive verbal comments or imagery related to the protected characteristics listed above.</li>
            <li>Deliberate intimidation, stalking, or following — online or in person.</li>
            <li>Harassing photography or recording of attendees or speakers without consent.</li>
            <li>Sustained disruption of talks, workshops, or other events.</li>
            <li>Inappropriate physical contact and unwelcome sexual attention.</li>
            <li>Advocating for, or encouraging, any of the above behaviour.</li>
            <li>Retaliation against anyone reporting a concern in good faith.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Sponsors, exhibitors, and recruiters are subject to the same
            standard. Booth staff should not use sexualised imagery, clothing,
            or activities. Hiring conversations are welcome; pressuring
            attendees is not.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Reporting a concern</h2>
          <p>
            If you experience or witness behaviour that violates this Code of
            Conduct, please tell us. You can:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Email the PGConf Poland Code of Conduct team at
              <a href="mailto:coc@pgconf.pl">coc@pgconf.pl</a>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Speak to any member of the conference team in person — we will
              be wearing identifiable badges and will be available throughout
              the day at the registration desk.
            </li>
            <li>
              If you would prefer to escalate to PostgreSQL Europe directly,
              or if your concern involves a member of the local team, you can
              email <a href="mailto:coc@postgresql.eu">coc@postgresql.eu</a>.
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Reports can be made anonymously, but providing contact details
            allows us to follow up with you and gather any additional context
            we need.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>What happens after a report</h2>
          <p>
            Reports are read by a small Code of Conduct response team. We will
            acknowledge your report quickly — usually the same day during the
            conference, and within 48 hours at other times.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will discuss the report with you, ask any clarifying questions,
            and decide on an appropriate response. Possible responses include
            a private conversation with the person involved, a formal warning,
            removal from the event without refund, exclusion from future
            PostgreSQL Europe events, and — where appropriate — referral to
            local law enforcement.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will respect the wishes of the reporter when deciding how to
            proceed, to the extent possible while still keeping the wider
            community safe.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Confidentiality</h2>
          <p>
            We treat all reports as confidential. Details of an incident will
            only be shared with the small group of people necessary to handle
            the response. We will not publish the names of either reporters
            or the people reported about without their explicit consent,
            except as required by law.
          </p>
          <p>
            Aggregate, anonymised information about reports may be shared
            with the wider PostgreSQL Europe board for the purposes of
            improving the policy and running future events.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Scope</h2>
          <p>
            This Code of Conduct applies to the conference venue (ARCHE Dwór
            Uphagena Gdańsk), all official social events, and all online
            spaces associated with PGConf Poland 2026 — including the
            conference website, mailing lists, chat channels, and any social
            media accounts operated by the conference team.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Credit</h2>
          <p>
            This Code of Conduct is a faithful summary of, and adheres to, the
            <a href="https://www.postgresql.eu/about/policies/coc/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer external">
              PostgreSQL Europe Code of Conduct</a>, which itself draws on the
            broader PostgreSQL Project Code of Conduct. Where there is any
            ambiguity, the PostgreSQL Europe Code of Conduct is authoritative.
          </p>
        </section>

        <div class="rule rule--center"></div>
        <p class="signoff">
          Questions about the policy? Email
          <a href="mailto:coc@pgconf.pl">coc@pgconf.pl</a> or
          <a href="mailto:coc@postgresql.eu">coc@postgresql.eu</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .coc-head { padding: var(--section-pad-y) 0 var(--space-10); background: linear-gradient(180deg, var(--color-bg-sunken), var(--color-bg)); }
  .container--prose { max-width: 65ch; margin-inline: auto; padding-inline: var(--section-pad-x); }

  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-eyebrow);
    font-size: var(--fs-xs);
    color: var(--color-gold);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
  }
  .coc-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--fs-4xl);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--color-fg-strong);
    line-height: var(--lh-tight);
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-tight);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }
  .coc-lede {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--fs-xl);
    color: var(--color-fg);
    line-height: var(--lh-snug);
    font-weight: 300;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-8);
  }
  .rule {
    width: 100px; height: 2px;
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--color-gold), transparent);
  }
  .rule--center {
    margin: var(--space-12) auto var(--space-6);
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, transparent, var(--color-gold), transparent);
  }

  .coc-body { padding: var(--space-12) 0 var(--space-20); }

  .coc-body section { margin-bottom: var(--space-12); }
  .coc-body h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--fs-2xl);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--color-fg-strong);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
    line-height: var(--lh-snug);
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-snug);
  }
  .coc-body h2::after {
    content: '';
    display: block;
    width: 48px;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--color-gold);
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
  }
  .coc-body p, .coc-body li {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    color: var(--color-fg);
    font-size: var(--fs-lg);
    line-height: var(--lh-loose);
  }
  .coc-body p { margin: 0 0 var(--space-4); }
  .coc-body ul {
    padding-left: 0;
    list-style: none;
    margin: var(--space-2) 0 var(--space-6);
  }
  .coc-body li {
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }
  .coc-body li::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 0.85em;
    width: 12px;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--color-gold);
  }
  .coc-body a {
    color: var(--color-gold);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
    text-decoration-thickness: 1px;
  }
  .coc-body a:hover { color: var(--color-gold-bright); }

  .signoff {
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--fs-sm);
  }
</style>
